\f1\i\b0 \cf2 Pre-Socratic Ontology as Essential Christian Assumption\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\i0 \cf2 \
The Pre-Socratic philosophers (6th\'965th century BC) laid the foundational questions of being, reality, and substance that remain essential to Christian ontology. Though these thinkers were pre-Christian and often speculative, their insights into first principles (archai) prepared the intellectual soil for biblical revelation and the Logos theology central to Christian faith.\
\
This primer explores how Pre-Socratic ontology\'97the study of being\'97serves as an essential assumption for Christian thought, particularly in the context of biblical cosmology, Christological metaphysics, and TruText theology.\
\
I. What is Ontology?\
\
Ontology (from 
\f3 \uc0\u8004 \u957 \u964 \u959 \u962 
\f2 , ontos, \'93being\'94 + 
\f3 \uc0\u955 \u972 \u947 \u959 \u962 
\f2 , logos, \'93study\'94) is the study of:\
	\'95	Being: What it means for something to exist.\
	\'95	Essence: What a thing is by nature.\
	\'95	Substance: What a thing is made of and how it persists over time.\
\
The Biblical Ontology of Genesis 1:1\
\
Genesis 1 begins with a cosmological assertion of being:\
\
	\'93In the beginning, God created the heavens and the earth.\'94\
\
	\'95	Being: God as the eternal I AM (Exodus 3:14).\
	\'95	Essence: God as Creator, distinct from creation.\
	\'95	Substance: Creation as spoken into existence (dabar/logos).\
\
II. Key Pre-Socratic Ontological Concepts and Christian Parallels\
\
The Pre-Socratics sought to understand the arch\uc0\u275  (
\f3 \uc0\u7936 \u961 \u967 \u942 
\f2 , \'93first principle\'94)\'97the origin and sustaining reality of all things. These inquiries resonate deeply with biblical truths.\
\
1. Thales (Water as the Essence of Life)\
	\'95	Thales: Water as the principle (arch\uc0\u275 ) of life and being.\
	\'95	Biblical Parallel: \'93The Spirit of God hovered over the waters\'94 (Gen 1:2).\
	\'95	Christian Insight: Water as baptismal reality\'97the medium of new creation (John 3:5).\
\
2. Heraclitus (Logos as Cosmic Fire)\
	\'95	Heraclitus: Reality is flux, governed by the Logos as a rational principle.\
	\'95	Biblical Parallel: \'93In the beginning was the Logos\'94 (John 1:1).\
	\'95	Christian Insight: Christ as the eternal Word, unifying all things.\
\
3. Parmenides (Being is Absolute and Unchanging)\
	\'95	Parmenides: True being must be unchanging and eternal.\
	\'95	Biblical Parallel: \'93I the LORD do not change\'94 (Malachi 3:6).\
	\'95	Christian Insight: God as the uncaused cause and eternal I AM.\
\
4. Empedocles (The Four Elements)\
	\'95	Empedocles: Reality arises from the four elements\'97earth, water, air, fire.\
	\'95	Biblical Parallel: Creation emerges from divine ordering of chaos.\
	\'95	Christian Insight: These elements echo the sacramental signs of baptism (water), Eucharist (bread/grain), and Pentecost (fire).\
\
5. Anaximander (The Boundless - Apeiron)\
	\'95	Anaximander: The Apeiron (boundless, infinite) as the source of all things.\
	\'95	Biblical Parallel: \'93The heavens declare the glory of God, and the skies proclaim the work of His hands\'94 (Psalm 19:1).\
	\'95	Christian Insight: God\'92s infinity and omnipresence as both transcendent and immanent.\
\
