Heraclitus	Fire/Logos	Logos (John 1:1)\
Parmenides	Eternal Being	I AM (Exodus 3:14)\
Empedocles	Four Elements	Sacramental Elements\
Anaximander	The Boundless (Apeiron)	God\'92s Infinity\
\
III. Pre-Socratic Ontology and the Christian Revelation of Being\
\
A. Biblical Ontology in Genesis and John\
	\'95	Genesis 1: Being arises from God\'92s spoken Word (dabar).\
	\'95	John 1: The Logos is the pre-existent Christ, through whom all being is made.\
\
B. The Triune Ontology of God\
\
The Trinity embodies a self-contained reality of being:\
	\'95	Father 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f2  Source of Being (Arch\uc0\u275 ).\
	\'95	Son (Logos) 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f2  Expression and Order of Being.\
	\'95	Spirit 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f2  Presence and Movement within Being.\
\
IV. Why Pre-Socratic Ontology Matters for Christian Thought\
\
1. It Provides Philosophical Vocabulary for Theology.\
	\'95	Theology requires a language of being to articulate truths about God\'92s nature.\
\
2. It Grounds Faith in Reality.\
	\'95	Christian faith is not mythical but ontological, grounded in the truth of existence itself.\
\
3. It Clarifies the Creator-Creation Distinction.\
	\'95	The arch\uc0\u275  of Christian ontology is God, not matter. Creation is contingent on God.\
\
4. It Protects Against Modern Relativism.\
	\'95	Being is objective. The denial of absolute reality collapses under the weight of self-contradiction.\
\
V. Practical Applications for Christian Theology\
\
1. Defending the Reality of Truth\
	\'95	Modernism: Reduces truth to subjective perception.\
	\'95	Christian Ontology: Insists that truth is objective and revealed in Christ.\
\
2. Ethics and Morality\
	\'95	Ontology of Goodness: God is the source of all moral reality.\
	\'95	Pre-Socratic Parallel: Goodness is not a construct but rooted in being.\
\
3. Biblical Interpretation\
	\'95	Genesis 1 as Ontology: Creation is not poetry but a declaration of being.\
	\'95	Logos Theology: Christ is the full expression of divine ontology.\
\
VI. Conclusion: Pre-Socratic Ontology as a Biblical Key Frame\
\
The Pre-Socratic philosophers laid a foundation of being, essence, and truth that Christian theology fulfills and transcends. Their seeking after wisdom echoes the biblical cry:\
\
	\'93The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom\'94 (Proverbs 9:10).\
\
To embrace Christian ontology is to:\
	\'95	Acknowledge God as the eternal being.\
	\'95	Recognize Christ as Logos, the Word of Creation.\
	\'95	Live as creatures of truth, defined by divine reality.\
